PICC, Shenhua Energy, Sun Hung Kai: Hong Kong Stock Preview

-- B y   H a n n y   W a n
-- 
2011-02-15T01:02:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-15/picc-shenhua-energy-sun-hung-kai-hong-kong-stock-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index  advanced 1.3 percent to 23,121.06. The
Hang Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, gained 2.6 percent to 12,398.05.  China may further increase its interest rates in the first
quarter because of pressure from rising consumer prices, the
State Information Center said in a research report published in
the China Securities Journal newspaper.  Chinese developers: China may raise the interest rate on
existing mortgages for second homes to between 1.1 and 1.2 times
the benchmark rate under a trial program in Beijing and  Shanghai ,
the 21st Century Business Herald reported, citing an
unidentified person close to banks.    China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd . (688 HK), controlled
by the nation’s construction ministry, advanced 1.8 percent to
HK$13.52.  China Resources Land Ltd . (1109 HK), a state-
controlled developer, climbed 3.5 percent to HK$13.18.  Property investors, retailers: Sales at  Sun Hung Kai
Properties Ltd .’s (16 HK) 12 major shopping malls in Hong Kong
gained as much as 30 percent last year to more than HK$10.8
billion ($1.4 billion), the South China Morning Post said,
citing Maureen Fung, general manager of the company’s leasing
department. Fung said she expects revenue at the malls will
increase by 20 percent this year, the newspaper said.  Sun Hung Kai will raise rents by as much as 20 percent on
leases coming due this year, the Post said.  Sun Hung Kai, the city’s No. 1 developer by market value,
gained 1.8 percent to HK$126.  Wharf Holdings Ltd . (4 HK), owner
of two of Hong Kong’s largest shopping malls, rose 0.1 percent
to HK$53.15.  Sa Sa International Holdings Ltd . (178 HK), the
city’s biggest cosmetic retailer, jumped 4.9 percent to HK$4.25.    China Shenhua Energy Co. (1088 HK): The listed unit of the
country’s biggest coal producer said January coal sales rose 16
percent from a year earlier to 27.9 million metric tons. The
shares rose 3.9 percent to HK$30.75.  China Southern Airlines Co. (1055 HK): The carrier said it
aims to double flights servicing the southwestern Chinese region
of Guangxi in the next five years. The stock surged 6.5 percent
to HK$4.09.  Orange Sky Golden Harvest Entertainment (Holdings) Ltd.
(1132 HK): The film studio that made Bruce Lee famous delayed a
planned sale of yuan bonds in Hong Kong, according to a person
familiar with the matter. The stock slid 1.8 percent to 54 Hong
Kong cents.  PICC Property and Casualty Co. (2328 HK): China’s biggest
non-life insurer said direct premium income in January was 18.3
billion yuan ($2.8 billion). The stock climbed 2.6 percent to
HK$9.72.    ZTE Corp . (763 HK): China’s second-biggest maker of phone-
network equipment said it will release Light 2 this year, a 10-
inch touch-screen version of its Light tablet with Google Inc’s
Android software. The stock gained 1.5 percent to HK$30.70.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Hanny Wan in Hong Kong at 
 hwan3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 